{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_morton_ver01/data/sn83045462/0028065999A/1929111801/0229.xml":{"full_text":"4\nFEDERAL RESERVE\nBARES CREDIT ACTS\nPart of System in Stock\nCrisis Is Revealed in\nMonthly Bulletin.\nExplanation of the part thf Federal\nReserve System and the New York Fed\neral Reserve Bank took during the criti\ncal period in r.he stock market in Octo\nber In extending credit to New York\nbank'! which took over brokers loans of\nnon-banking lenders is contained In the\nmonthly Federal Reserve bulletin, made\npublic yesterday.\nCombined figures of weekly reporting\nmember banks in the leading cities, the\nbulletin said, showed an increase in\ntotal loans and investments of $1,600\n000.000 from October 2 to October 30.\nnearly all of which occurred dtiring the\nlast week of the month and at banks\nin New York City.\nThe taking over of this credit, the\nbulletin continued, was reflected in a\ngrowth in the last week in October of\n$1,500,000,000 In net demand deposits of\nthe New York banks and of a conse\nquent large growth of tnelr reserve re\nquirements. which was Indicated by an\nincrease of $240,000 000 in their reserve\nbalances with the Federal Reserve Bank.\nSyslrm Aided Banks.\n\u201cIn coming to the support of the sit\nuation dtiring this period of severe dis\nturbance the banks In New York City\nhad the assistance of the Federal Re\nserve system.\" the bulletin added \"The\nFederal Reserve Bank of New York-in\ncreased its discounts for member banks\nbv $150,000,000 during the week and In\naddition purchased $150,000,000 of\nUnited States Government securities in\nthe open market. As a consequence of\nthe action of the banks in New York i\nCity and of the Federal Reserve Bapk\nof New York, the liquidation which\ntoo kplace in the security market was i\nnot associated with a rise in money\nrates.\nRates on cg(j money, which had de\nclined from a range of R t,o Piper cent!\nin September to 6 per rent in the latter\npart of October, ranged between 5 and j\n6 per cent during the last week of that\nmonth.\u2019\u2019\nThe board reviewed the decrease In\nbrokers loans during the latter part of\nOctober when a total reduction for the\nmonth of $2.400.000.000 in brokers' bor- j\nrowings was reported by the New York i\nStock Exchange.\nForeign Money Is Withdrawn.\n\u201cLoan? to brokers by non-banking j\nlenders declined by $2,000,000,000 dur-\ning October, reflecting withdrawals of\nfunds from the call-loan market by\nforeign lenders, investment and trad-,\nlng companies and other corporations!\nand individuals.\u201d the bulletin said\n\"Loans to brokers for out-of-town\nbanks, which include a considerable\namount of loans for the account of their\ncustomer*, decreased by $800,000,000,\nwhile loans by New York City talks,\nfor their own account increased bv\nii. ooo.ooo.ooo.\u201d\nIndustrial activity, the bulletin said, j\nwhile larger in August and September\nthan year ago. showed a decline forj\nOctober as compared to a year ago. but\nonly because the increases were not as\nlarge as those of 1928, which was a year\nof high production. Total production.\nthe report continued, was 11 per cent\nlarger for the first- nine months of the\nyear than for the corresponding period.\nof 1928. The total output of automo- j\nbiles In September was about the same\nas in the same month a year ago, the\nboard said.\nBuilding Volume Holds.\nThe volume of residential building\ncontracts awarded in September de\nclined. but public works and commer-\nrial and industrial building continued I\nin large volume.\nNotwithstanding the decline In the\npast, is months.\u201d the bulletin said, \"the\nvolume of construction, as measured by\ncontracts awarded, has remained at a\nhigh level, compared with earlier years.\u201d\n\"Notwithstanding the slackening of\nIndustrial activity in the past two\nmonths.\u201d the board concluded, \"factory\nemployment, and wage payments to in 1\ndus trial workers, which has been in\ncreasing -for the past two years, re\nmained In large volume this Autumn, j\nEarnings of industrial workers, there-\nfore, have been maintained, and there\nappear? to be no considerable change!\nin the income of farmers, a? compared\nwith last year. The sustained buying\npower of both industrial and agricul\ntural workers has been reflected In a\nlarge volume of distribution of com\nmodities by railroads and in a growth\nin retail sales to ultimate consumers.\"\nLIEUT. WALTER HINTON\nTQ SPEAK TO OPTIMISTS\nWorld Flight Pilot to Tell of i\nPlane\u2019* Utility in Modern j\nDevelopment.\nLieut. Walter Hinton of world flight\nfame, chairman of the aviation com\nmittee of the Washington Chamber of\nCommerce, will be the principal speaker J\nat the weekly luncheon meeting of the\nWashington Optimist Club Wednesday\nafternoon at the Hamilton Hotel.\nLieut. Hinton, it is announced by\nHerbert B. Mevius. president of the Op-1\ntimist Club, will speak on his world\nflight, his flight to the far north and\nof his exploration? in the Brasilian:\n.\u2019tingles.\nHe also will speak on the utility of!\nthe airplane in today's stage of its de\nvelopment and of plans for the estab\nlishment of up-to-date facilities for air\npassenger, mail and express sendee into\nand out of the Capital.\nDUTY IS LOWERED.\nBritain Granted Smaller Hate by\nArgentina on Artificial SilV.\nOable to The Star.\nBUENOS AYRES. November 18.\u2014\nPresident Hipollto Irigoyen signed a\ndecree Saturday reducing import duties\n50 per cent, on British artificial silk\nniece goods and on cotton and woo!\npiece goods containing a proportion of\nartificial silk. The decree was issued\nwith the understanding that the British i\nwould undertake, not to levy or Impose\nany restriction on the entry of Argen\ntine meat and wheat into England, be\nyond neressarv sanitary restrictions.\nwe pay Regular Savings\nM No matter how small the\nm amount is, if it is deposited\nm regularly it will assure you\nM of financial independence. We\nStart in saving today!\nOR MORE Open dotty t to 5 financed\nSaturday until noon\n\u201cA\nu on xonr\nV Sntinfi RATIONAL Ci,y\nPERMANENT H l,\nRl II.OINO ASSOCIATION pw\n(ORGANIZED 18901\n949 Ninth Street N.W.\nJuaf SelotL .Vets yorfc Apenua W|H i\nCjU\u00abt C. I. Irtunrr\n'hoover to discuss\nBUSINESS \"RELIEF\u201d\nWITH RAIL LEADERS\n\u2019Continued From First Page.t\ni ness. Secretary Lamont of the Depart\nment of Commerce said today. He said,\ntoo. that the Government would look\nto existing agencies in the business\nworld *o aid in carrytng forward the\nprogram. His own department and the\nUnited States Chamber of Commerce. I\nMr. iJtmont. said, would be among the\n\u2022genctes utilized, and. in addition, the\nAmciican Federation of Labor and ihe\nAmerican Bankers' Association. If a 1\nco-ordinating agency, bringing the j\ni Government and ali the commercial I\nand labor organisations into closer\n\u2018ouch, is found to be necessary, it will\nbe set ud later.\nThe name? of a number of America's\nimportant bustness and banking ex-\necutives have been mentioned In con-\nnectlon with the President'* confer\nences. Among them are those of Owen\nD Young. Thomas W. lament of J. P.\nMorgan As Co., and Julius Barnes\nchairman of the board of the United\nState? Chamber of Commerce and 1\nArch W. Shaw of Chicago. Mr. Young\nserved as chairman of the committee\non unemployment several years ago. and\non a later committee dealing with the\neconomic .situation. Others mentioned i\nare J. P. Morgan and Henry Ford.\nIt Is expected that Mr. Hoover will j\nlay before the conferences complete in-\nforma lion, obtained by the Govern-\nment. regarding the business situation\nand activities in all lines. With rhis\ninformation at. hand tt. is believed that\nthe representatives of industry, agrl- I\nculture and labor will be in a position\nto go ahead with a well co-ordinated j\nprogram.\nWagner Approves Plan.\nThe President's program for assist- I\nance to business was given indorsement\nby Senator Wpgner of New York, a\nDemocrat, who has made a study of\nthe employment situation and who ha?\nurged that Congres? adopt a plan to;\nprevent widespread unemployment in i\ntimes of depression by planning public i\nworks for a long time Bhead, which\nmay be undertaken when the need\ncomes Senator Wagner said:\n\u201cThe great, danger Inherent in the\npresent disturbance of the public\nmind.\u201d said Senator Wagner, \"is that\n1 It may develop into a spell of unem\nl ployment. That must be guarded,\nagainst and prevented at all costs.\nIt has been repeatedly asserted and j\n1 established that present-day prosperity\ndepends upon tk>e buying power j>f the j\ngreat masse* of \u00abhe people. Nothing\nsustains that buying power a* much,\nas the assured expectation that em\nployment, will continue and that wages j\n1 will be earned. t\n\"If there 1* doubt of the future. It 1\nrepidlv turns to fear, which congeal*\nthe desire to purchase and causes all\neconomic activities to shrink.\nUrged Passage as Bill.\n\"For the last two years I have re- 1\npeatedly urged upon Congress the de\ni sirablltty of passing my bill providing\ni for the long-range planning of public\nworks and the creation of an agency\nto co-ordinate such activity. The meat t\nof that plan is that public agencies\nshould so order the construction of pub\nlic work* as to stabilize employment\nand prevent unemployment. The bill\nhas received the universal approval of\neconomists and ha? in principle been\nrecommended by the Senate commit-\nj tee which investigated unemployment,\nj \u2018Had the bill been enacted there\nwould now be no need for hasty con- 1\nferences, which in themselves seem to i\nforebode distress. The superiority of a\npermanent, responsible agency con-;\ntinuously making the necessary adjust\nments to provide stability over panicky\nI conferences In the midst of an\nemergency is too obvious to require\ni elaboration.\"\nBIG PRECEDENT SET.\nHoover Back in Bole of Engineer- 1\nBusiness Man.\nBY DAVID MWtENn\ni President Hoover regards the oppor\ntunity to bring about co-operation be\ntween Government and business a? cov\nering not merely the readjustment\ngrowing out of the recent stock market\ndecline, but as a permanent project. I\nIt- was Mr. Hoover who immediately j\nafter the war preserved through the re\nconstruction period many of the com\nmodity divisions set up in tne various\nparts of the Government for war pur\nposes. What the President is endeav- j\noring to do now would have been sub\nject to widespread criticism if he had\nattempted it under normal conditions.\nThe crisis, if it can be called such, i*\nindeed made to order for the engineer\nbusiness man in the White House. It Is\nthe kind of emergency in which he la\nperfectly at. home, particularly since he\ncan avoid politics and call to confer\nence leaders from all industries, classes\nand parties.\nGroup Meeting* Slated.\nThe program for the week has been\ndivided inio group meetings. First comes\nthe conference with railroad executives, i\nThe announced purpose is to expedite\ni construction. The railroads have been\nhesitating to buy steel rails and author\nize large construction projects to take\ncare of the growing freight of the coun\ntry because they did not know what,,\nconsolidation plans might be developed\nwhich would Interfere with their ar\nrangements. The assumption now is\nthat Mr. Hoover will try to get an agree- j\nment of some kind on consolidation so\nthat the Interstate Commerce Commis- i\nsion can unscramble the situation in\nI which the problem has foundvitself for\n1 several years.\nNext is the grpup conference with the\nbankers, representatives of manufar-\nhiring concerns, pnniic utility compa-\nntes and various trade? and distribution j\nagencies. The plan here is to eocouragp 1\npireproof garage or ware\nhou\u00bbe, about 30,000 square\nfeet. National 3000.\nFOR RENT\ne\nTwo Bedroom*, Liv\ning Room, Dining Room.\nKitchen, Bath and Re\nception Room. Electric\nRefrigeration.\nTHE ARGONNE j\n16th Sc Columbia Rd.\nI\n\nTHE EVEXIXG STAR. WASHINGTON. n. r.. MONDAY. NOVEMBER I*. 1?^\n\nwhich have been held in abeyance due\nto high money rates.\nThe later conferences will deal with\nthe construction of terminal and ware-\nhouse facilities for agriculture a* well!\n1 a* the expediting or construction on i\npublic buildings for the Federal, State\nand municipal governments.\nNever before in time of peace ha?\nthere been such a concerted move made\nto direct the course of American bust- i\nness. It establishes a precedent of such\nfar-reaching proportion* that, nobodv\nhere is ready to predict the outcome,T\nfor it mean* that the Federal Govern-\nI ment. under the leadership of the Pres\nidem, and rhe department heads, has\nattempted a work of co-ordination of\nbusiness and industry which, if at\ntempted even under normal circum\nl stances, would be of vital importance to\nthe economic welfare of the country.\nIn times of prosperity, however, gov\nernmental Influence is exerted delicately\nand is often brushed aside by leaders\nin Indus.ry as unwairanted interfer-1\nencc. With the Nation united now In\nan effort to preserve the gains made by\nindustry the last few years, the leader-!\n1 ship of the Government 1* not liketv to\nbe challenged.\nCongress may be wrangling about\nthe tariff and other phases of political\ncontroversy, but It is a foregone con\nelusion that if any tegialation is re\nj quired 10 assist in the movement which\nI has for its obiect the stimulation of\n1 business, approval will be given as rap-\nI Idly as was the recent suggestion of tax\nj reduction.\nThe monthly announcement by the\nFederal Reseive Board indicating that\n'there was *ome failing off in business\nin certain lines long before the stock\nmarket decline occurred is taken to\nmean that business has b\u00aben in process\n\u2022of readjustment already and that Mi*\nstock market was late in discovering\nI Its error in exaggerating the earning\nj i>ower of basic industries\nIt is recognized here that no real\neconomic upset has occurred in the\n1 major lines of business and that the\nj important thing to be done now is to 1\ni prevent a depression in mood from\ni nrtnging on a depression In fatt. The\nconferences called by President Hoover\nand the activity which is expected to 1\nresult therefrom may be regarded as\na definite step toward preservation of\nconfidence in a business outlook which\nthe fact-finding agencies of th\u00b0 Gov- i\ni eminent insist is entirely healthy and i\nsubstantial, though perhaps not com-\n1 paring with previous high records.\n(Copyright, tart. I\nSPEAKERS APPOINTED.\ni Jewish Congregation* I*t Plan*\nfor Tour.\nIn representing Washington Jewish\norganisations in the November tour of\nthe Union of American Hebrew Congre- j\ngations. Dr. Abram Simon will speak in\nPhiladelphia December 20 and Mauri ic\niD. Rosenberg in Richmond Novem\nber 22.\nTour representative* will include 300\nrabbts and laymen, who will visit more\nthan 200 citle*. David A. Brown. New\nYork banker, is national chairman of\nthe tour.\ni Hebrew organizations associated with\nthe union are the National Federation\nof Temple Sisterhoods. National Fed\ni eratlon of Temple Brotherhoods He\nbrew Union College and the department\nof synagogue and school extension.\nFRENCH SUB LAUNCHED.\nSurcouf One of Largest Under\nwater Vessels in World.\nCHERBOURG. France. November 18\nOP). \u2014The French navy\u2019s newest sub\nmarine. one of the largest in the world\nwas launched here today and chris\ntened \"Bureouf.\" after the famous\nBreton naval commander.\nThe submarine is 400 feet long and'\nlls of 4.000 tons displacement. It can\ni dive to a depth of 450 feet.\n1 a\ntwo interesting members\nof the search for Santa Claus\nMEET THEM IN\n\"A CHRISTMAS\nADVENTURE\u201d\n\nA Jolly Trip to the\nNorth Pole and Santa i\nClaus Land for AH\nthe Kiddies\nBEGINS MONDAY, NOV. 25th\nin\nj\n\u00a3ljc Jstar\nTHE GREAT NEWSPAPER OF THE NATION\u2019S CAPITAL\nI\ni\nWhen you are\nbilious\n\u2014don\u2019t let your system stay clogged.\nExpel food* waste promptly with 25c\nEpsotabs \u2014the sate, modern laxa- _ t __\ntive that\u2019s easy and pleasant to take. 60 in hox ioT\nEpsotabs are Epsom Salts com*\npounded in tablet form and\nsugar-coated. No incon* /\\jYp\u00ab5L\nvenience. Insist on the\ngenuine. At druggists. gHL f\nWrite for /tee sample\nTHE DILL CO.\nlad ether food iraj stores y|r\nHonors business\nPARLEY SOON DUE\n.Program Outlined for Confer\nence Called to Survey Fi\nnancial Conditions.\nPresident Hoover s preliminary con- j\nterence to sustain business conditions\nmeets this week. Its steps will be based\ni upon a survey of such changes as\nmay now be taking place, and esti\nmates about probable future conditions, t\nIn much that, is now printed on this\nsubject there is a conscious or sub\nconscious motive to avoid infecting j\nthe countrv with unnecessary pessim\nism. Hardly any motive could be more\nworthy. In what is said here, how\never, thi* motive is dismissed. The\npresent article alms to as detached a\nsummary of information and views ,pre-\nsented as coldly as the coming confer-\nence will itself approach the subject. j\nFor several weeks preceding the\npanic on Wall Street, there was an j\nebbing of activity In a group of lines,\nj typified by building construction. These\nwere lines in which the cost of bor-\nrowing money on bonds is a basic\nfactor. The reason for ebbing in these\nlines was the excessive absorption of\nmoney In Wail Street. By the defla\ntion in Wail Street this money ts re- j\nleased. Business dependent on bond\nissues had been dammed back and this\ndam is now broken.\nfAnir Viewed as Helpful.\nIt is anticipated, therefore, that the\npanic will have a helpful effect on these\nand all lines of business in which the i\ncast of borrowing money counts heavily.\nWhether this anticipation will be ful\nfilled as respects ordinary building eon\nstruction is open to argument, both\nways. That road construction 'will bp\ni revived and stimulated is certain.\nThere are plans already under way\n1 which assure that,. Every other form\n1 of business activity will be stimulated\nthat, depends on the power of cities.\nStates and corporations to borrow i\nmoney at, low rates.\nPreceding the Wall Street panic there\nwas one other line of business In which\nsign? of recession had begun. That was\nthe motor industry. The cause of that\nreccsssion was believed to be different\nfrom the cause described above. In the\nmotor industry, in the belief of some j\nleaders of ft, sales had been stimulated\nover a long period to a point where, as\nrespects domestic consumption, some\nrecession was due. The counterbalance\nto the condition lies In foreign consump\ntion. Some leaders in the motor Indus- i\ntry believe that foreign consumption Is\nstili in the stage in which American\nconsumption was 20 vears ago. These\nleader* believe there is enough potential\nexpansion in the foreign field to take\nup any slack that may develop in do\nmestic consumption.\n\"Luxury Buying\" Halted.\nTo turn to the direct effects of the\npanic, there is one that practically\nevery one admits. There will be a\nfalling off of what is called luxury buy\ning. This means the sort of buying\ndone mainly by the rich when in the\nexpansive mood arising out of big and\neasy profit* In speculation. It is pos-\nGradaat*\nMcCormick Medical Glaasct Fitted\nCellete Ere, Examined\nDR. CLAUDE S. SEMONES\nEyesight Specialist\nPhene National 07!I\n463-410 Mrl.achten Bid*,\nlath and G Rta. N.W.\n\nsible for this mood of abstinence from\nbuying to extend to circles other than\nthe rich and other than those who\nspeculate. That such an infection of\nmood, if widely extended, would have\nan effect of retarding volume of trade\ngoes without saying This constitutes I\nthe leading psychological factor in the j\nsituation.\nThat such a condition is unnecessary t\nand not warranted by the other factor* 1\niin the situatiem is the belief held\nstrongly and also coldly by persons in\ni the best position to judge. They are i\ni confident that the net of all the future\nI 'renditions, if wisely guided and co\nordinated. need result in no material\ncurtailment of the buying power of the\nj American public.\nFactors in Situation Cited.\nIn holding this judgment thev rely\nupon certain factors, some arising out\nof the very panic itself, which act as i\na counterbalance to the panic. One of i\nthere factors is the abundance of money\n1 and abundance of credit. They hold\nthat this abundance is Irresistible as a\nforce making for volume and activity\nof business.\nThe only interruption they concede\nj is one that, might, occur during the\nbrief period required for money and\ncredit to make the journey from Wall\nStreet back to its normal repositories\n1 in the banks of the country and in the\nl treasuries of corporations.\nThat thus panic cannot be attended\nby money famine or credit famine i\u00ab\nthe distinction which marks it off from\ni every previous Wall Street panic of\ni the same kind. On the contrary, due to\nthe existence of the Federal Reserve\nsystem, this panic is inevitably bound\nto be followed by abundance of money\nat markedly low rates and interest.\n\nSUSPECT IN LARCENY\nCASE HELD IN SOUTH\nFormer Executive of D. C. Shoe\nStore AiTested in\nFlorida.\nRoy Henderson. 35 years old, who is\nunder indictment, here on charges of\nembezzlement, larceny after trust and\ngrand larcenv, has been arrested bv\npolice In Clearwater. Fla., ending a\nsearch for him by District police for\nmore than two years.\nDetective Rergt. Howard F. Ogle left\ntoday for Clearwater to bring Hander\nson *o this city for arraignment in\nthe Supreme Court on six counts of\nlarceny and embezzlement from the\nLincoln Shoe Store at 1115 G street,\ni involving a total of $l,lOO. Hender\nson was assistant manager of the shoe\nstore.\nThe nllegfd embezzleme